[Student "S"]
{You have an easy 1\S opening bid.

But East overcalls 2\D and partner bids 3\D.

You should be certain to have a partnership agreement on the meaning of a cue-bid after an overcall.

Most good players use it to show support for opener's suit and at least 11 points. In other words, a hand with which you would have made a limit-raise or better.

So you bid the \S game.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \DA, then \DK, then \DJ. West discards on the second \D and ruffs the third one with the \ST.

<b>North plays 4\S. East leads the \DA, then \DK, then \DJ. West discards on the second \D and ruffs the third one with the \ST.</b>

Losers: \S 0? : \H 1 : \D 2? : \C 0 : Total = 3?

The loser count looks a little messy - that's because of the circumstances. If you could have just played three rounds of \Ss you would probably have had 0 losers, and if you ruff this \D you will have only 2 \D losers, but maybe create a \S loser.

But though the loser count is confused your plan should not be. You <b>DO NOT</b> over-ruff the \ST. Instead you discard your one \H loser (a loser-on-loser play). West can have this trick but whatever he returns you will win, pull trumps in <b>THREE</b> rounds if necessary, and take the rest of the tricks.

Discarding the \H loser instead of over-ruffing was the winning Plan. If you had over-ruffed you would have lost the \H, but you would also have to lose a trump. You made a good play.

But did you notice that East made a bad play? He should have cashed his \HA before he led the third \D for his partner to ruff. Then when his partner ruffed with the \ST your goose would have been cooked. }
[Play "W"]DA

